</div>
<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<aside class="introtext">Noam Chomsky offers insights on issues ranging from Iran to Latin America and the risk of nuclear war under Trump.</aside>
<p>For over a half a century, Noam Chomsky, celebrated linguist and current Laureate Professor of Linguistics and Agnese Nelms Haury Chair at the University of Arizona, has provided intellectual and moral leadership to critics of American foreign policy. In the interview below, conducted in his office at the University of Arizona on August 7, 2018, Chomsky discusses the American obsession with Iran, and why the Trump administration seems ready for a confrontation. He also addresses the disappointing trends in two Latin American nations, Venezuela and Nicaragua. Above all, Chomsky expresses his concerns over nuclear weapons, especially in the unpredictable hands of Donald Trump. Reprinted below is the text of the interview edited for format and clarity.</p>
<p><strong>Saul Isaacson: In the larger sense, do you believe that there is still a reservoir of untapped anti-Semitism in the United States?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Noam Chomsky:</strong> It&rsquo;s not even untapped. Take the strongest supporters of Israel, the Christian evangelicals. That&rsquo;s the most anti-Semitic group in history. Even Hitler didn&rsquo;t say that all Jews should go to eternal perdition. Can you be any more anti-Semitic than that?</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255394">
<h2>Stay in the loop</h2>
<p>Never miss the news and analysis you care about.</p>
